## B.23 One more shortcut list

If you type these at the REPL you get useful output immediately:

```
(help 'help)
(describe 'describe)
(type-of type-of)
(apropos \"intros\")
(macroexpand '(let ((x 1)) x))
(map car (snapshot-registry))
```

Try each. Read the output. That is the whole introspection surface in six commands.

## B.24 The truly final note

The cheat-sheet is a scaffold. The reflexes are the point. Once the reflexes are automatic, the cheat-sheet becomes redundant — you will not need to look it up because your fingers will already type the right verb.

Aim for that state. Print the cheat-sheet, use it for a week, then throw it away.

Onward to Appendix C.

## B.25 Extended prose — why each verb earns its place

For a reader who wants to understand the shape of the cheat-sheet, not just memorize it, this section explains why each verb category matters.

The verb-metadata section (B.1) exists because verbs are the primary units of the language. Every question you might ask about a piece of Motoi code starts with a verb. Being able to describe, doc, contract, arity, source, and examples any verb is the foundational reflex. Without these seven verbs, you are guessing.

The value-shape section (B.2) exists because values are the second primary units. Every computation produces values; every debugging session inspects values. Knowing the runtime type, the length, the keys, the fields — this is the difference between reading a printed result and understanding it.

The predicates (B.3) exist for conditional dispatch. When your code needs to branch on a value's shape, predicates give you the boolean checks. They are the counterpart to `type-of` — one returns a symbol, the other returns a yes/no.

The env section (B.4) exists because scope is a real thing and can be walked. Most languages hide scope; Motoi exposes it. When a closure's behavior surprises you, walking its captured env tells you what it captured.

The macro section (B.5) exists because macros generate code. Without seeing the generated code, you cannot debug the generation. `macroexpand` is the microscope.

The reader section (B.6) exists because the interpreter operates on forms, not strings. The reader is the strings-to-forms step. When you want to metaprogram, you go through the reader.

The errors section (B.7) exists because failures are informative. An error record has more data than an error message. Introspecting the record is faster than parsing the message.

The trace and watch section (B.8) exists because sometimes you need the temporal dimension. A snapshot is a moment; a trace is a story.

The Cortex section (B.9) exists because programs remember. Reading what a program remembers is as fundamental as reading what it computes now.

The registry section (B.10) exists because the language surface is itself a value. Iterating it, filtering it, projecting fields — these operations turn the language into a queryable data structure.

The search section (B.11) exists because you cannot remember every verb name. Search bridges the gap between what you want and what to call it.

The LLM-augmented section (B.12) exists because sometimes mechanical introspection runs out and a peer verb can go further. Grounded, honest, always distinguishing what the registry knows from what the model guesses.

The composer section (B.13) exists because widgets are a live projection of forms. Introspecting a canvas is introspecting the form the widgets produce.

The performance section (B.14) exists because measurement precedes optimization. Time, fuel, memory — three axes, three verbs each.

The REPL section (B.15) exists because sugar matters. Meta-commands are shortcuts; the underlying verbs are the reality.

The five reflexes (B.16) are the whole book distilled to five habits. If you build these five reflexes, the book has done its job.

The compositions (B.17) show that the primitives combine. Five verbs, five patterns, infinite variations.

The verbatim reference (B.20) is the copy-paste layer. When you need the exact call form, it is there.

## B.26 The cheat-sheet as pedagogy

A cheat-sheet like this one is meant to be a scaffold, not a crutch. The intent is that you consult it often at first, less over time, and eventually not at all — because the verbs have moved from the paper on your desk to the muscle memory in your fingers.

If a cheat-sheet is doing its job well, you outgrow it. That is the goal. Print this page. Use it for a week. Come back to check the syntax of a verb you forget. Come back less often. Eventually stop looking. That is what proficiency looks like.

## B.27 A closing observation

The introspection surface is small enough to fit on one sheet of paper. That is remarkable. Most language reference sheets run to dozens of pages because the language surface is enormous. Motoi's introspection surface is 30-40 verbs, and they compose enough that a reader who has memorized 15 of them can express queries that would take hundreds of API calls in another language.

Small language, deep introspection, one sheet.

Onward to Appendix C, where a 40-line REPL extension demonstrates every verb this sheet listed in a working project.

## B.28 An expanded task-index

For finding the right verb quickly, indexed by the task you are doing:

**\"I want to know what a verb does.\"** — `(describe 'foo)` or `(doc-of 'foo)`.

**\"I want to see a working example of a verb.\"** — `(examples-of 'foo)`.

**\"I want to see the source code of a verb.\"** — `(source-of 'foo)` gives you the pointer.

**\"I want to check what a value's runtime type is.\"** — `(type-of value)`.

**\"I want to see the keys of a hash.\"** — `(keys hash)`.

**\"I want to see what bindings are in the current scope.\"** — `(env-vars (current-env))`.

**\"I want to see what a macro expanded to.\"** — `(macroexpand '(macro-use args))`.

**\"I want to see what my last error was.\"** — `(last-error)`.

**\"I want to know why the program remembers something.\"** — `(cortex/query ...)` with provenance.

**\"I want to enumerate every verb in a namespace.\"** — `(verbs-in-namespace \"ns\")`.

**\"I want to search for a verb by keyword.\"** — `(apropos \"keyword\")`.

**\"I want to time an expression.\"** — `,time <expr>` or `(current-time-ms)` deltas.

**\"I want the LLM to explain a value.\"** — `(explain value)` or `(shape-of value)`.

**\"I want to audit a cart's permissions.\"** — filter registry by `:perm` (see B.9 and B.10 combined).

Fourteen tasks, fourteen answers. Every one is one or two verbs. That is the practical shape of the surface.

## B.29 Onward

Cheat-sheet complete. Turn to Appendix C.

## B.30 One final reference — the verb dispatch model

Because it comes up in every appendix, one more explanation of how the introspection layer works under the hood.

When you call `(help 'car)`, this happens:

1. `car` is parsed as a symbol.
2. `help` is looked up in the current environment — it is a registered verb.
3. The `help` verb's implementation is called with the symbol `car` as its argument.
4. The implementation converts `car` to its name string `\"car\"`.
5. The implementation looks up `\"car\"` in the registry via `getVerbMeta`.
6. The registry returns the metadata object.
7. `help` shapes the metadata into a plist and returns it.
8. The REPL prints the plist.

Eight steps. All standard verb dispatch plus a registry lookup. Introspection is not a special path in the runtime — it is a regular verb that happens to consult metadata.

Same for `describe`, `type-of`, `source-of`, and every other introspection primitive. They are all verbs. They all go through dispatch. They all return data. They all compose.

## B.31 The universal claim

Every introspection question in Motoi is answered by a verb that consults the registry or the runtime state and returns data. No verb requires a special mode. No verb writes to disk unless it says it does. No verb bypasses the dispatcher's perm check.

Uniform, honest, composable. That is the introspection layer.

Onward to Appendix C.

